## Articles

- [The death of the drag-and-drop builder](https://blog.dugong.live/): The site's lead essay (Dispatch Nº 47). For fifteen years workflow automation looked like a canvas of rectangles connected by lines; after watching three million runs across twelve thousand teams, the Dugong team argues the canvas itself was always the problem. Makes the case for describing a workflow in plain language and letting a compiler turn it into running automation with triggers, branching, and integrations, instead of hand-wiring brittle node graphs. By Aanya Rao, 2026-05-28.
- [How to stop discount codes from applying to sale items on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-stop-discount-codes-applying-to-sale-items-on-shopify.html): You run a sale by lowering prices and setting compare-at prices so the strikethrough shows, a shopper adds the marked-down items, then pastes the welcome code from your popup at checkout, and Shopify applies it on top, so a 40 percent sale quietly becomes 46. This is one of the most repeated questions in the Shopify community ("how do I exclude sale items from discount codes," "stop customers using welcome codes on sale products," "discount code applying on top of already reduced prices") and the answer is that no native switch exists. The combination settings only govern how discounts combine with other discounts, and a sale made by editing prices is not a discount to the engine at all, it is just a price, so a sitewide code applies to markdowns exactly as it applies to full-price items. The workarounds route through eligibility: an automated collection keyed off compare-at prices, with codes scoped to the inverse full-price collection, which decays as the sale rotates, cannot always be applied to codes already issued, and never covers the codes that popup, loyalty, and review apps mint sitewide on their own. Shopify Scripts, the old Plus-only backstop that stripped a code when it met a markdown, stopped executing on June 30, 2026, so stores that relied on one are now double-discounting in the open. Doing it by hand decays fast: the collection drifts with every reprice, marketing forgets the eligibility step on new codes, and the misses only surface in the margin report. And no toggle holds the real policy anyway, because some codes should go through: a service-recovery code should work on anything, a creator code might deliberately touch the sale, a loyalty voucher might stack up to a floor and no further. The Dugong playbook treats it as a policy that runs everywhere discounts are born and land: read the rule in plain language, keep the on-sale and full-price collections true on every price and compare-at change, scope each new code on creation including app-minted ones, guard checkout by resolving the single best discount when a code meets a markdown, tell the shopper plainly why the code did not stack, and hold for review the support code on a sale item, the stack that slipped through, and any floor breach. Framed as a compiler problem because whether a specific code may meet a specific markdown is judgement that changes per code, per product, and per campaign. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-20.
- [How to add a gift message and gift wrap option at checkout on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-add-a-gift-message-and-gift-wrap-at-checkout-on-shopify.html): A shopper buys a present, types a note at checkout, and pays to have it wrapped, then the box lands at the recipient with the sender's full invoice inside and no message anywhere. Shopify has no dedicated gift field: the only native place for a note is the cart order-note box, one unlabeled freeform field built for delivery instructions, off by default in many themes, with no validation and no signal that this is a gift. Gift wrap at checkout is native only for Shopify Plus on Checkout Extensibility, and even then a bare toggle rather than a fee, a line item, and a bench instruction. The worst failure is the packing slip: it is one template for every order and it prints prices, with no native switch to hide totals for a gift, so the recipient sees what the sender paid. Doing it by hand rests on someone spotting a note and picking the right template during the fourth-quarter rush, and it cannot hold the judgement calls: the empty or abusive message, the gift shipping to a different address, the cart that is half gift and half self-purchase, the split shipment. The Dugong playbook captures the gift toggle, wrap choice, and message as order attributes, validates and cleans the note, attaches wrap as a real line item or fee, tags the order as a gift, builds a gift packing slip with the message in and prices out routed to the bench, and holds offensive or oversized messages, multi-address gifts, and split shipments for a human. Framed as a compiler problem because whether a message is fit to print, where the gift ships, whether the price shows, and whether the wrap reached the bench is judgement that changes per order. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-18.
- [How to set up tiered volume discounts (buy more, save more) on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-set-up-tiered-volume-discounts-on-shopify.html): You want the oldest offer in retail, buy more and save more: buy 3 save 10 percent, buy 6 save 20, buy 12 save 30. You open Shopify's discount screen, build the first tier, go to add the second, and there is nowhere to put it, because a Shopify discount holds one condition and only one. This is one of the most-repeated frustrations in the Shopify community ("tiered discounts based on variant quantity," "tiered buy X get Y discount," "how do I do buy more save more without an app," "why does my tiered discount only apply one tier"). Give Shopify its due first: the native automatic discounts are genuinely good at the simple case, buy 3 get 10 percent off applies cleanly with no code and no app, and you can gate a discount to a collection, a minimum quantity, or a minimum spend. The wall is that each discount holds a single condition, so buy 3 save 10 is one rule and buy 6 save 20 is a second, separate rule, and there is no way to chain them into one storefront offer that steps the saving up as the cart grows. Faking it with three automatic discounts backfires: a cart with 12 units qualifies for all three, Shopify does not pick the best tier and suppress the rest, so the shopper can land on the smallest saving or the discounts refuse to combine, and there is a hard cap of 25 active automatic discounts so the one-discount-per-tier approach runs out of room fast. The one place Shopify does real quantity tiers is B2B, where quantity pricing on a price list behaves like a proper ladder, but it applies only to customers assigned to a company profile, not to the open storefront, not to tagged retail customers, and not to a cart-total tier a first-time visitor should see. And the old escape hatch is gone: Shopify Scripts, the way Plus merchants faked tiered cart pricing for years, stopped executing on June 30, 2026, so any store that ran buy-more-save-more through a Script now has a broken checkout and is pushed toward Shopify Functions or a discount app built on them. Doing it by hand is a maze of overlapping automatic discounts and coupon codes that turns fragile the moment a sale or a newsletter code is also running, because the combination settings are coarse and a volume tier stacked on a code can quietly push an item below cost, and no tier table can hold the judgement that margins differ per product, that wholesale and retail should not see the same breaks, and that a deep tier during a promotion is a different decision from a permanent price. The Dugong playbook treats it as a resolver plus a guardrail plus a nudge running on every cart change: read the tier table, the breaks, whether they key off units or spend, and the audience; resolve the single highest tier the cart has actually earned; apply only that tier to the right lines or the whole cart, never a smaller one by accident; guard stacking by enforcing whether it can combine with a code or a live sale and holding each tier above its margin floor; show the shopper the next rung so add two more to save 20 percent does its own upselling; and hold for review a tier that would cross a floor, a code clash, or a new promotion that overlaps an existing ladder. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more grid of quantities and percentages, because whether a cart earned a tier is arithmetic but whether applying it alongside a code crosses the floor, which audience sees the deeper ladder, and whether a new promotion overlaps a live one is a judgement that shifts per product, per audience, and per promotion window. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-16.
- [How to automatically sync bundle inventory with component stock on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-sync-bundle-inventory-with-component-stock-on-shopify.html): You sell a gift set and the candle, the soap, and the bath bomb inside it never move a single unit, because Shopify counts the bundle as its own product with its own stock number, so the parts oversell on their own pages while the bundle keeps selling after the shelf behind it is empty, and a shared component drifts out of step across every bundle it lives in. This is one of the most-repeated complaints in the Shopify community ("bundle inventory not updating," "how do I sell a bundle of two products and make the inventory go down," "my bundle shows sold out but the items are in stock," "components not deducting when the bundle sells"). Give Shopify its due first: the free Shopify Bundles app does link a fixed bundle to its components and shows the bundle as available based on the lowest-stock component, so it will not let you sell a kit whose parts are gone, and for a store that builds every bundle through that app and keeps them simple that linkage is real and does the core job. The trouble is how narrow the happy path is and how many stores fall off it. The native app caps a fixed bundle at a limited number of components and variants, so a big mix-and-match builder outgrows it; it does not track true mix-and-match bundles the same clean way, so the "build your own six-pack from any of these twenty" offer, the one that most needs component math, is the one it handles worst; it tracks a bundle against overall component stock rather than per location, so a store shipping from two warehouses can sell a bundle in a place that cannot assemble it; and it does nothing for the enormous number of bundles merchants built the older way, as a standalone product or a single variant with its own inventory number, which carries a count no component sale ever touches and no bundle sale ever pushes back down to the parts. Then the seams break even a linked bundle: edit an order after it is placed, remove a bundle, add one, change a quantity, and the component math does not re-run, because Shopify never modeled the relationship as something an edit should recalculate; and sync your catalog to another channel or a marketplace and the bundle usually travels as one atomic SKU, so selling ten kits on your store leaves the component still showing its full quantity on the channel you were not even watching. Doing it by hand collapses the instant a component is shared, because one candle sitting in a starter kit, a deluxe set, a gift box, and its own product page means selling any one of those should drop the real candle count and recompute how many of each of the four listings can still be offered, and across a catalog that sells all day you are always one sale behind, which on inventory means always either overselling something you cannot ship or hiding something you could, and the judgement creeps in on top, because a component at zero is not the same as one you chose to backorder, a returned gift set may have come back with two of its three items so adding a whole bundle's stock back is wrong, and a component sold both on its own and inside kits may need a reserve held so the bundles you already promised can still be built. The Dugong playbook treats it as a source of truth plus a cascade plus a reconciliation that runs both ways: on any sale, return, restock, or order edit that touches a bundle or one of its components, resolve the bundle to its recipe of which parts and how many including the hidden ones; deduct each component's real stock, per location, by what the sale consumed; recompute every bundle's availability as the largest full set its parts can still build so it never sells past the stock behind it and never hides while the parts are in stock; cascade a shared component to every bundle and product page that depends on it; sync the corrected counts to the other channels so a marketplace stops showing stock the bundle just consumed; and hold for review a negative component, a partial return, or a zeroed bundle better sent to backorder than hidden. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more field mapping a bundle to its parts, because whether a bundle is out is arithmetic but whether to hold a reserve for already-promised kits, credit a partial return, or backorder a zeroed set is a judgement about a specific component at a specific moment that shifts per component, per location, and per order, which a fixed rulebook handles badly and a person cannot hold across a catalog that moves all day. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-15.
- [How to automatically pause ads for out-of-stock products on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-automatically-pause-ads-for-out-of-stock-products-on-shopify.html): A product sells out at two in the afternoon and your Google and Meta ads keep running it until well past midnight, sending paid clicks to a page where the only button says Sold Out, and you pay for every one of them. Shopify never paused the ad, because it does not pause ads at all, it syncs a feed on a schedule, and the money keeps going out the door in the gap. This is one of the most-repeated complaints in the Shopify community ("Cant run ads due to out of stock item," "Google advertises my out of stock items," "how do I stop wasting ad money on products that are sold out"). Give Shopify its due first: the Google and Meta sales channels connect your catalog to a product feed that carries an availability attribute for every product, so when stock changes the channel updates the feed and a sold-out product is eventually marked out of stock, and for a store that never wired a feed by hand that sync is real and more than you would build yourself. The trouble is everything it does not do. First, the sync runs on a schedule rather than the instant stock hits zero, so there is a lag between the sale that empties your shelf and the feed that admits it, and Google and Meta then re-crawl and re-approve on their own clocks on top of that, and through the whole gap the ad keeps serving and the meter keeps running. Second, the channel updates the feed but never pauses the campaign or ad set on the platform, and for a Performance Max or Advantage+ Shopping campaign the platform decides what to show across your entire feed, so a single out-of-stock item does not stop spend, it just shifts it around, sometimes onto other things you did not intend. Third, when the feed and the live product page disagree about availability, which the lag guarantees, Google routinely disapproves the product, and a pile of disapprovals drags on the health of the whole account, so the stale feed wastes spend on the dead product and quietly hurts the ads for the products still selling. It helps to put a number on it: a store spending a few thousand a month on shopping and social, with a normal spread of bestsellers going in and out of stock, can easily send five or ten percent of a day's budget to products that are already gone, and it concentrates where you bid hardest because the fastest sellers run out first. None of it touches the thing merchants keep asking for, a rule that lives in the store, watches inventory, and pauses the ads for a specific product the moment it is not worth advertising, then turns them back on when it is, and there is no toggle in Shopify admin that does that. Doing it by hand falls apart on two words, which thing: pausing the whole campaign turns off your in-stock products too, and pausing only the sold-out item means finding its exact placement in each account, the listing group inside a Performance Max campaign, the specific ad in a standard search or shopping campaign, the catalog item or ad set in Meta, and matching it back to the Shopify product and the variant that ran out, then remembering to turn it back on the second stock returns or doing the mirror-image damage of a fully-stocked bestseller sitting dark. It rewards a fast, reversible decision made per product, per variant, and per hour, which is exactly where a person loses and a fixed automation misfires, because a product at one unit is not one at zero, a product restocking tomorrow is not one gone for the season, and a product out in one size while three others sell should not have its ad killed. The Dugong playbook treats it as detection plus a match across systems plus a judgement plus a reversible action in two ad accounts and a feed: on a product or variant crossing your stock threshold, match it to its ad placements across Google and Meta; read whether it is truly out, low but restocking soon, or out in one variant while others still sell; pause only the affected placement, never the whole campaign, so the in-stock products keep running; correct the feed availability to match the live page so the product stops getting disapproved and the mismatch stops dragging on the account; resume the ad and the listing the moment inventory returns above the threshold, without anyone logging into the ad accounts; and hold for review a flickering bestseller, a budget worth reallocating to other products, or a restock landing within the hour. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more threshold field, because whether an item is out is arithmetic but whether to pause its ad, hold it live for the learning, or move the freed budget somewhere it can sell is a judgement about restock timing, campaign optimization, and media strategy that shifts per product, per platform, and per hour, which a fixed rule handles badly and a person cannot keep up with across a catalog that moves hourly. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-12.
- [How to limit purchase quantity per customer on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-limit-purchase-quantity-per-customer-on-shopify.html): You cap a hot product at two per person, the drop sells out in minutes, and the orders list tells the real story, the same name or address or card over and over, each order neatly at or under your limit, adding up to a stack of units that was supposed to reach dozens of people. The cap you advertised did nothing, because Shopify never counted the customer, it only ever counted the cart. This is one of the most-repeated requests in Shopify merchant communities running drops, flash sales, collabs, and allocation-limited products ("limit quantity per customer," "stop one person buying all my stock," "why does my two-per-order limit let someone place ten orders," "enforce one per customer during a launch"). Give Shopify credit for the part it does: the native add-to-cart limit, set under checkout preferences, caps the maximum quantity of a given product a shopper can put in one cart, and for stopping an obvious over-buy in a single transaction it works and is worth turning on. But a per-cart limit is not a per-customer limit, and the native rule hits three walls the moment you are protecting a real allocation: it is per variant, not per product or per customer, so a tee sold in three colors with a limit of two lets one shopper take two red, two blue, and two green in the same cart, six units against a limit that reads like two; it resets on every order, because the limit lives on the cart, so the instant a checkout completes the counter is gone and the same person can start a fresh cart and buy again with nothing tracking the running total across their orders; and it does not know who the customer is, never looking at email, address, card, or account, so it cannot tell that twenty separate orders are one buyer, and it does not apply in Shopify POS, on draft orders, or for B2B profiles. The heart of a purchase limit is a single move Shopify does not make, recognize the buyer across orders, keep a running count of what they have already taken, and refuse the order that pushes them over, and everything Shopify gives you stops one step short of it. The common workaround, code on the product or cart page that blocks the button once the quantity is too high, is invisible on every other path into checkout, so the Shop Pay, Apple Pay, and Google Pay wallet buttons, a buy-it-now button, a saved cart link, and a checkout permalink shared in a group chat all skip it, and underneath even that sits the harder problem of identity, because a limit that keys off a logged-in account is walked around with a guest checkout or a second email and one that keys off a browser cookie is beaten by an incognito window or a cleared cache, so the people you most want the limit to stop are the ones most willing to open a new tab. A broken limit does its damage at the worst possible moment on the product you least wanted to lose, the launches, collabs, restocks, and allocation-constrained lines where demand outruns supply, and when the cap fails a small number of buyers clear the inventory in minutes, real customers hit a Sold Out page and remember it, the units end up on a resale market at a markup, and the goodwill you were spending the drop to build turns into a wall of "why can't I ever get one" replies. The usual moves each cost something: the add-to-cart limit caps the cart and leaves the customer completely uncapped; cart-page code covers one path, breaks on the next theme update, and never counts what the same person bought an hour ago in a different session; requiring accounts adds friction that costs real conversions and still waves through a reseller with a burner email; a Shopify Flow reacts to the order after it is placed and fires one order at a time, so it can help clean up afterward but cannot hold a running per-customer total or block the checkout before the money moves; and an order-limit app enforces a fixed rulebook the same way to every order and cannot notice that two orders to the same building are a genuine couple rather than one reseller, that a wholesale account should be exempt, that an order is a gift going elsewhere, or that a near-match is too uncertain to cancel on automatically. The Dugong playbook treats it as a read plus an identity match plus a decision plus an action at checkout plus a set of corrections: on a new order or checkout, read the items and quantities and the per-customer limit for this product, collection, and launch window; identify the buyer across orders by email, shipping and billing address, payment fingerprint, account, and device; decide whether this order takes them over the limit once you add what they already bought in the window; enforce at checkout on every path in, the cart, wallet buttons, buy-it-now, saved links, and checkout permalinks; clean up what slipped by cancelling or trimming the excess, refunding it, and restocking the units for real customers; tell the customer the limit clearly and confirm kindly when an order was trimmed to the cap; and hold a shared-address household, a wholesale exempt, a gift, or an uncertain match for a human. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more quantity field, because whether an order is over the cap is arithmetic but whether to cancel it is a judgement about identity, households, wholesale, and gifts that shifts per order, per customer, and per minute of a launch, which a fixed rulebook handles badly and a person cannot watch across a flood of orders at once. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-11.
- [How to automatically add a free gift to the cart on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-automatically-add-a-free-gift-with-purchase-on-shopify.html): You set up a spend seventy-five, get a free gift promotion, a customer crosses the threshold, and the free gift never appears in their cart, because a Shopify discount only reduces a price, it never adds the item to the cart. A free gift with purchase is one of the oldest and best-behaved promotions in retail, it lifts the average order, clears slow stock, and turns a maybe into a checkout, but the platform never puts the gift in the bag. The native Buy X Get Y discount genuinely handles one shape, a fixed product-specific bundle (buy this product or something from this collection and get this item free or at a percentage off), and for that it prices the cheapest qualifying item to zero cleanly. Most gift offers are not that shape, and the native rule then hits three walls: it only ever reduces a price and never adds the item, so if the gift is not already in the cart there is nothing for the discount to touch and nothing appears, leaving the shopper to know about the gift, find it, and add it themselves; there is no store-wide cart-value trigger, because Buy X Get Y fires on the presence of specific products or collections and not on a total spent across anything, so the most common offer of all, spend one hundred on whatever you like and get a free gift, is not something the native rule can express; and it supports only one tier per discount and will not stack, so you cannot natively say seventy-five for the small gift and one-fifty for the big one in one offer, and because Shopify applies only the larger discount when two would land on the same item, an existing sale can silently swallow the gift. The common workaround, cart-page code that adds the gift when the subtotal crosses the line, leaks because a modern Shopify store has many doors into checkout that never touch the cart page, the Shop Pay, Apple Pay, and Google Pay wallet buttons that jump straight from the product page, a saved cart link, a buy-it-now button, a checkout permalink shared in an email, so a gift added by cart-page code is simply absent on all of them, and code that only ever adds also leaves the gift on a cart that has fallen back below the threshold, leaking real product one order at a time. A broken gift offer is worse than no offer at all, because a promotion that never delivers the thing it advertised makes the customer feel cheated, generates the where-is-my-gift ticket, and trusts the next banner less. The usual moves each cost something: Buy X Get Y automates the pricing of a gift the customer still has to find; cart-page code covers one path and misses the wallet-button and checkout-link paths and breaks on the next theme update; a Shopify Flow reacts to the order after it is placed, too late to put the gift in the cart before payment, so it can tell you the offer should have fired but cannot make it fire; and a free-gift or BOGO app adds the item and can watch a cart value, which is real progress and proof the native gap exists, but applies a fixed rulebook the same way to every cart and cannot notice that a gift is about to sell out and should fall back to another, that a shopper is gaming the offer to collect several gifts across split orders, that a returned order kept its free item, or that this cart already carries a bigger promotion the gift should not stack on. The Dugong playbook treats it as a read plus a decision plus an action on the live cart plus a stream of corrections: on a cart changing, read the subtotal after discounts, the items in it, and who the customer is; decide the right gift from your rules, the threshold crossed, the tier reached, the customer segment, and any product exclusions; add the gift and price it to zero so the customer never has to find it or pay for it; hold on every path into checkout, the cart page, the wallet buttons, saved links, and checkout permalinks; swap or remove the gift when the cart drops below the threshold, crosses a higher tier, or loses the qualifying item; honor stock so it never gifts an item it cannot ship and falls back to the next gift when one runs out, while telling the customer what they earned and how far to the next tier; and hold a near-empty gift, a gamed cart, a kept-gift return, or a risky stack for a human. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more rules table, because whether a cart qualifies is a rule but whether to gift it right now is a judgement about stock, gaming, stacking, and refunds that shifts per cart, per customer, and per hour of a sale, which a fixed rulebook handles badly and a person cannot watch across every live cart at once. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-08.
- [How to automatically split and route Shopify orders to multiple suppliers](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-automatically-split-and-route-shopify-orders-to-multiple-suppliers.html): A customer fills one cart and pays once, but the items inside come from three different places, one your own warehouse holds, one a supplier makes to order, and one a dropshipper ships direct, and to fulfill it someone has to take that single order apart, decide which line belongs to which vendor, write a separate order for each with only their items and the customer's address, send them off, then days later gather the tracking back and mark the right pieces shipped. Shopify shows you the order but does not split it, route it, or send it anywhere. This is one of the most-repeated requests in Shopify merchant communities running multi-supplier and dropship catalogs ("automatically send each supplier only their part of the order," "split an order by vendor," "email a purchase order to my dropshipper when a sale comes in"). Shopify does split fulfillment across your own stocking locations when one lacks stock, and can offer split shipping at checkout, which covers a slice of the need, but that split is by location, not supplier: it decides where to fulfill from by which location has stock and your location priority, not by the rule you care about, which is that this brand of item is always made by that vendor and this other one always ships from the dropshipper. There is no rules engine for routing (you cannot tell Shopify to send anything tagged one way to supplier A and anything over a weight to the freight partner and have it group the lines and act); the vendor field on a product is only a label useful for filtering and reports that notifies no one, generates no purchase order, and routes nothing; and there is no native way to email or post each supplier a document with only their line items in the format they accept (email, CSV, portal, EDI). Shopify Flow can react when an order is created, tag it, and on higher plans move line items between locations, but it has no action that groups lines by supplier, builds a purchase order with just that supplier's items, sends it, and then fulfills only their lines when the tracking returns, so it can notice a multi-supplier order but cannot carry it across each vendor to done. The order also comes back in pieces on each supplier's own clock, so each shipment is a partial fulfillment that has to be recorded against the right lines at the right location with the right tracking, or you either mark the whole order shipped before two thirds of it exists or leave delivered lines open. The usual workarounds each cost something: emailing every supplier by hand caps growth and is the first thing to break during a sale; the native multi-location split routes to a location, not a vendor you can send a PO to; setting the vendor field and building a Flow stops halfway because Flow cannot build and send the per-supplier order or close it out; and an order-routing or dropship app applies a fixed rulebook the same way to every order and cannot notice a supplier that has gone silent, a backordered line that should wait, a destination that changes the cheapest source, or a split that fragments a delivery for no reason. The Dugong playbook treats it as a read plus a classification into supplier groups plus a document build per vendor plus a send plus a chain of partial fulfillments that close over time: on a paid order, read every line item with its vendor, SKU, type, and weight, the destination, and the shipping speed paid for; group the lines by who fulfills each, honoring which location has stock, the destination region, and cost; build one purchase order per supplier with only their items, the ship-to address, and your reference; send each supplier their PO in the format they accept and record the split against the order so nothing is sent twice; fulfill only a supplier's lines when their tracking returns, at the right location, as a partial; tell the customer once what ships from where and when rather than a confirmation per fragment; and hold an item no supplier covers, a backordered line, a split that would ship one item from two places, or a supplier that has gone silent for a human. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more rules table, because whether a line has stock at the location the rule points to, whether the supplier has been responsive, whether a backordered item is better held than routed, and which case to escalate shift per order, per supplier, and per day, which a fixed rulebook handles badly and a person cannot keep up with across a growing catalog of vendors. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-07.
- [How to automatically send invoices to Shopify customers](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-automatically-send-invoices-on-shopify.html): A business customer buys from you, and a day later the email lands asking for a proper invoice with their company name and VAT number, because what Shopify sent at checkout was an order confirmation, which lists what was bought and paid and reads like a receipt because that is what it is. It is not an invoice, it does not carry the buyer's tax registration number, and in most countries it is not the document an accountant will accept, so the merchant opens a template, retypes the details, generates a PDF, and emails it by hand, again for every business order. This is one of the most-repeated requests in Shopify merchant communities ("send a proper invoice automatically," "where is the field for a customer's VAT number," "why does the order confirmation not count as a tax invoice"). Shopify does automate the order confirmation email, and Shopify Tax can generate a VAT invoice for orders shipped within the EU and UK and display it on the order status page, which covers a real slice of the need. But that confirmation is a receipt, not an invoice, and carries no tax numbers; the VAT invoice Shopify Tax produces is never emailed to the customer, is region-locked to the EU and UK, offers almost no customization, and cannot be regenerated after an order is edited; and most fundamental of all, Shopify's standard checkout has no field for the customer's tax or VAT registration number, collecting only a company name in the billing address, so the single detail a business-to-business invoice legally needs is the one the platform never captures at the source. The usual workarounds each cost something: renaming the order confirmation to "invoice" is a receipt in a costume, with no tax number, no sequential invoice series, and no credit note on a refund; the Shopify Tax VAT invoice automates one region's happy path and leaves other markets and every changed order manual; a PDF invoice app adds a download link to the confirmation email (Shopify does not let its emails carry attachments, so it is a link not an attachment) but applies one fixed template to every order and does not decide receipt vs tax invoice, validate the VAT number, or know reverse-charge rules; and regenerating each sale in Xero or QuickBooks gives clean books but doubles the handling across two systems. The Dugong playbook treats it as a classification plus a data capture plus a compliant document build plus a reversible credit note: on an order being paid, and again on any refund, read the order (line items, tax, discounts, shipping, customer, consumer vs business); decide whether it needs a plain receipt or a full tax invoice and apply the buyer country's format; fill the VAT or tax number from the order notes, a past order, or the customer record, and ask once if it is genuinely missing; generate a compliant, sequentially numbered PDF with both parties' details and a correct tax breakdown; send it automatically in the order email and to the buyer's accounts address without waiting to be asked; issue a matching credit note against the original invoice number when the order is refunded in part or full; and hold for a human a VAT number that fails validation, a reverse-charge or export order, or an edited order whose invoice must be reissued. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more template, because whether an order needs a receipt or a tax invoice, whether the tax number is present and valid, and which case to escalate shifts per order, per customer, and per market, which a fixed template handles badly and a person cannot keep up with across a growing book of business buyers. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-06.
- [How to automatically schedule product publishing on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-schedule-product-publishing-on-shopify.html): You plan a drop for midnight, set the product to publish on a future date, and go to bed, and it goes live on the online store and nowhere else, because Shopify's built-in future publishing only reaches the Online Store sales channel and never touches POS, the Buy Button, or your other channels. It also no-ops if the product is still in Draft at the scheduled minute, cannot bulk-schedule across channels in the native admin, and most tellingly will only ever schedule a product going live, never coming down. This is one of the most-repeated requests in Shopify merchant communities ("does product scheduling apply to all sales channels," "schedule a publish in bulk edit for another channel," "make a product unpublish itself on a date"): half of running a catalog is taking things off the shelf on time, a flash-sale product when the sale closes, a collab at the end of its window, a seasonal line the day the season ends, and Shopify has no native scheduled unpublish. The workarounds each cost something: publishing by hand ties a person to a midnight clock and to the end of the window; the native future-publish date lulls you into thinking the launch is handled while POS and the other channels sit empty, and silently does nothing if the product was left as a draft; Shopify Flow can run on a scheduled-time trigger and unpublish products but is gated to the Plus plan and is a build to wire and maintain; and a scheduling app applies its calendar mechanically without checking whether a product is genuinely ready, whether the drop has stock, or whether the timing clashes with another promotion. The Dugong playbook treats it as a readiness check plus a timed publish across every channel plus a timed take-down that runs both ways: read the whole launch set by tag or collection with its go-live time and channels; confirm each product is active, priced, and has stock or a pre-order plan before it goes live so a launch never fires a half-finished page; publish at the exact minute to the online store, POS, the Buy Button, and every channel it belongs on; unpublish the set the moment its window closes for a timed drop or sale; redirect the retired URL somewhere useful instead of leaving a dead product link; keep the set in sync as products are added or removed from the tag or collection; and hold for a human a product still in draft at go-live, a drop with no stock, or a launch time that clashes with another promo. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more date picker, because whether a product is truly ready to publish, whether a drop needs its ending scheduled too, and which clash to escalate shifts per launch and per channel, which a fixed rule handles badly and a person cannot keep up with across a calendar full of drops. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-05.
- [How to set a minimum order amount on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-set-a-minimum-order-amount-on-shopify.html): A customer adds one low-price item, checks out for a few dollars, and Shopify accepts the order even though the transaction fee, the pick and pack, and the shipping label cost more than the order earns, so you booked a sale that cost you money to fulfil. Setting a floor, a cart has to reach some amount before it can check out, is one of the most-repeated requests in Shopify merchant communities ("set a minimum order amount," "minimum spend before checkout," "minimum order quantity for wholesale"), and there is no native setting for it on standard plans. The minimum purchase field that exists lives on discounts and only decides when a discount applies, it never blocks a checkout; Shopify Plus can enforce a minimum at checkout with Functions (formerly Scripts); and B2B quantity rules apply only to company profiles, not the retail storefront. The two workarounds each cost something: cart-page JavaScript that disables the checkout button is bypassed the moment a customer checks out through a wallet button like Shop Pay or Apple Pay, a saved cart link, or a checkout permalink that never touches the cart page; and most apps enforce a single flat number for everyone, unable to tell a retail shopper from a wholesale buyer or to exempt a gift-card order. The usual moves fall short: a note in the cart is documentation without enforcement; a free-shipping threshold only rewards bigger carts and never blocks small ones; cart-page code covers one path and misses the rest; and a single store-wide minimum blocks the wholesale customer, the gift-card top-up, and the loyal repeat buyer you wanted to let through. The Dugong playbook treats it as detection plus judgement plus enforcement that holds on every path: read the cart on every route into checkout (subtotal, item count, customer, retail vs wholesale), decide the floor that applies here rather than one flat number, signal the shortfall early on the cart, enforce at checkout itself so a wallet button or saved link cannot slip under it, exempt the carts that should always pass, nudge the borderline cart over the line instead of only blocking it, and hold wholesale exceptions and one-off approvals for a human. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more flat number, because the safe call shifts per cart and per customer. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-05.
- [How to automatically hide sold-out variants on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-automatically-hide-sold-out-variants-on-shopify.html): A shopper opens a product page, looks for their size or color, taps it, and the button flips to Sold Out, because Shopify keeps the out-of-stock variant sitting in the dropdown or swatch right next to the ones in stock, usually grayed out or crossed off. The shopper reads Sold Out as the whole product being unavailable and leaves, even though the sizes on either side were buyable, so the dead variant quietly taxes conversion on the items you can still sell, and it is the best-selling size that goes out first, at the highest-intent moment on the page. This is one of the most-repeated requests in Shopify merchant communities ("hide specific variants when sold out," "hide out of stock product variants"). Shopify has no native setting to hide unavailable variants: it treats the variant list as part of the product's structure rather than a live view of what is buyable, so the theme renders every option value regardless of stock; turning off continue selling when out of stock only disables the variant, it still shows; and the newer unlisted status hides a whole product, not a single variant. The only real routes are editing the theme's Liquid so an option value stops rendering at zero inventory, which is brittle, tied to the theme, breaks on theme updates, and gets much harder once size and color combine because a color is only truly gone when every size in it is out, or installing a third-party app that hides on a fixed everything-at-zero rule that cannot tell a week-long stockout from a discontinuation. The usual workarounds each give something back: leaving it as Sold Out bleeds conversion invisibly on the best sellers; editing the theme does not stay fixed and a hide that fails to un-hide leaves an in-stock size no one can see or buy; unpublishing the whole product takes the in-stock sizes down with it and loses the page's search ranking; and deleting the sold-out variant destroys its SKU history, cost, and barcode and breaks any back-in-stock signup attached to it. The Dugong playbook treats it as detection plus judgement plus a reversible action that runs both ways: watch inventory per variant, color, and location; decide whether a sold-out one is briefly out and should stay visible with a back-in-stock capture or is discontinued and should be hidden; hide the value from the storefront without unpublishing the product; collapse a whole option only when every value in it is gone rather than leave an empty selector; keep the demand on hidden or unavailable variants with a signup; restore the variant the moment inventory returns and notify the waitlist; and hold for a human the discontinued lines, the core size that keeps flickering in and out, and the product where hiding would leave nothing to buy. Framed as a compiler problem, not one more toggle, because whether to hide, keep, or escalate a sold-out variant shifts per variant and per day, which a fixed rule handles badly and a person cannot keep up with across a catalog that changes hourly. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-03.
- [How to combine multiple orders from the same customer on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-combine-multiple-orders-from-the-same-customer-on-shopify.html): A repeat customer places a second order before the first one ships, and what should have gone in one box becomes two orders, two shipping labels, and two delivery charges the customer paid twice. Combining orders is one of the most-requested things Shopify still does not do natively: it treats every order as a fixed financial record with its own payment, tax, discount, and fulfillment history, so a merge would risk corrupting reporting and reconciliation, and Shopify keeps orders immutable and pushes consolidation out to a manual draft-order routine or a third-party app. The workaround, which Shopify Flow cannot automate, is several careful steps done before either order ships: rebuild both orders' line items into one draft, finalize and label it, add the tracking back onto the originals, refund the duplicate shipping, and cancel the originals while restocking so inventory stays accurate. The Dugong playbook runs the whole chain inside the pre-fulfillment window: match the pair by customer, email, and address; confirm they can safely combine and are not a shared building, a gift, or a paid express upgrade; build one shipment; refund the fair combined shipping; cancel or link the originals with inventory and books kept straight; message the customer once; and route anything ambiguous to a human. Presented as a compiler problem rather than one more button, because the safe merge depends on per-pair judgement a fixed rule makes badly. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-02.
- [How to stop card testing attacks on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-stop-card-testing-attacks-on-shopify.html): Card testing, also called carding, is one of the loudest complaints in every Shopify merchant community, and unlike most Shopify pains it arrives all at once, usually overnight: a merchant wakes to hundreds of tiny orders, each a few dollars on one or two cheap products, each with a different name, email, billing address, and card, most declined and a few approved, none of them real customers. A bot has found the checkout and is running a list of stolen card numbers through it to learn which ones still work, because a public store that will attempt a real charge for a small amount is the perfect test rig and a low-value charge is less likely to be noticed by the true cardholder; the fraudster does not want the product, they want the single bit of information, this card works or this card is dead, to sell or spend elsewhere. The pattern is only visible in aggregate: dozens or hundreds of orders in minutes, almost all the same low value, almost all on the same product, a huge share declined, each individual order looking almost plausible on its own. Three concrete walls: the native CAPTCHA fires on Shopify's read of risk, not the merchant's, because for Shopify Payments stores Shopify runs machine-learning models that can trigger a checkout CAPTCHA, which stops some crude bots but is bypassed by one that rotates IPs and spaces out attempts, so waves of card-testing orders and fake abandoned checkouts still get through; the cleanup is entirely manual, since every test order that landed is a real order on a stolen card the merchant must find, cancel, refund before it ships, and restock, one order at a time against a fraud clock, because the small slice that approved turns into chargebacks; and the rule engine is paywalled and blind to the pattern, because auto-cancel and auto-flag live in Shopify Flow on the Advanced and Plus plans (so the smaller stores hit hardest often cannot use it), and even there Flow reacts one order at a time and cannot see that forty orders in four minutes share a fingerprint, decide the store is under attack, and respond to the burst as a burst. Why it matters: a declined attempt is not free because the processor charges for the attempt, so a flood racks up fees even when nearly all fail; the few approvals become chargebacks with their own dispute fees; a spike in dispute rate can put the payment account under review or into a penalty tier, risking the ability to take money at all; and the flood buries real orders and poisons conversion and fraud analytics. The big mistake is treating each order alone, because one three-dollar order to a new name is nothing but forty of them in four minutes across forty cards is an attack, a distinction only visible in the aggregate. The usual workarounds break: raising the price does not deter a fraudster spending someone else's money and just makes each fraudulent order cost more; cranking every fraud filter up starts declining real customers and becomes its own revenue leak; cancelling by hand cannot keep pace with an attack that refills the queue while you work; and waiting for it to stop only moves tonight's fees, chargebacks, and poisoned metrics into next month. The AI playbook triggers on a burst of orders or checkouts that spikes above the store's normal rate, reads the whole burst (order values, card and email spread, IPs, products, decline rate, window) and decides attack versus real spike from the pattern rather than any single order, cancels and refunds the test orders before they ship and restocks the units, tags every test order and checkout so it drops out of revenue, conversion, and fraud metrics, throttles or blocks the offending IPs and sessions and tightens checkout only while the attack runs and keeps friction off the paths real customers use, alerts a human once with the window, count, and estimated fee exposure with the cleanup already done, and stands down when the attack stops while surfacing for review any real customer caught in the net or any approved charge that already shipped. By Priya Singh, 2026-07-01.
- [How to set up pre-orders on Shopify without holding in-stock items](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-set-up-pre-orders-on-shopify-without-holding-in-stock-items.html): A pre-order is the good problem until the order lands, because demand showed up before the stock did and the customer paid you anyway, and then Shopify hands you one order with two delivery dates trapped inside it. The hard part was never the selling, it is the stretch of time between purchase and delivery that has to be managed, and a mixed cart runs two timelines at once: the in-stock line wants to ship today, the pre-order line cannot ship for weeks, and Shopify models an order as one thing with one status, so the whole order waits on the slowest line in it and the in-stock item the customer could have had this week gets held hostage by the late one. Three concrete walls: there is no real pre-order, only a Continue selling when out of stock checkbox that lets a shopper buy past zero but shows the same Add to Cart button, carries no expected ship date, takes no deposit to charge later, and does not tag the order or the line item, so the sale lands looking like a normal in-stock order with nothing on it to say part of it cannot ship yet; nothing splits a mixed cart, the correct handling is a partial fulfillment that ships the in-stock line now and holds the pre-order line, but that is a manual step you take order by order and nothing flags which orders need it, tells the customer the order is arriving in two parts, or remembers to come back when the stock lands; and Shopify Flow, free on every plan, can react when an order is created, tag it, and notify you, but has no action that splits the cart and fulfills only the in-stock lines, charges a held pre-order balance later, watches incoming inventory and fulfills the pre-order line the moment it arrives, emails the customer a real ship date, or turns the continue selling toggle back off when the run sells out, so it can tell you a pre-order came in but cannot carry it from purchase to delivery. Why it matters: a customer who bought a now item and a later item and hears nothing assumes the whole order is broken and writes the ticket, a pre-order with no ship date feels like a charge with no product, and a run left selling after the units are gone oversells real stock and turns buyers into a refund queue. The big mistake is leaving continue selling on too long, which keeps selling past the units you have while the orders arrive untagged and the customer unaware anything is a pre-order, turning a controlled pre-order into plain overselling. The usual workarounds break: ticking continue selling sells the pre-order silently; listing the pre-order as a separate product splinters inventory, reviews, and ranking across two listings and forces a merge when stock lands; shipping everything together is the held-hostage problem stated as policy, with the in-stock item sitting in the stockroom for a month; and partial-fulfilling each order by hand does not scale past a launch of a few hundred pre-orders, where the open lines that fall through the cracks become the where-is-my-order emails. The AI playbook triggers on an order with a pre-order or backorder line, labels the order and the specific line items with the promised ship window, ships the in-stock lines now as a partial and holds the pre-order lines open, tells the customer what ships now and what ships later with a real date, watches incoming stock and fulfills each held line the day it lands oldest order first, updates the customer if the date slips and confirms when the held part ships, stops selling once the run is fully committed so it does not keep overselling, and holds oversells beyond the run, mixed refunds, and bad date slips for a human. By Priya Singh, 2026-06-30.
- [How to reconcile Shopify payouts with your sales](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-reconcile-shopify-payouts-with-your-sales.html): Reconciling payouts is the quiet Shopify chore that scales with every order you take, and the platform leaves the matching entirely to a human. The deposit that lands in your bank is never your sales: it is gross sales minus processing fees, minus refunds you issued, minus chargebacks and their fees, minus any held reserve, plus or minus adjustments, so a week that sold four thousand dollars might deposit thirty-seven hundred, and the missing money is fees and a refund and a hold, each of which belongs in a different account. On top of that, Shopify pays in batches on a rolling schedule, so one deposit usually covers part of one day and part of the next rather than a clean calendar day, and a single deposit can represent dozens or hundreds of individual orders and refunds rolled together, which is why no deposit ever equals a day's sales and you cannot match by date. Three concrete walls: the Payouts page reports but does not post, it breaks a payout into gross sales, fees, refunds, and net and lets you export a CSV, but nothing carries those figures into your accounting software as a real entry or matches the net to the bank feed; the official QuickBooks and Xero connectors sync order level data but were not built to split a batched, netted payout into its parts and tie it to the deposit, so either the deposit is recorded as fresh income on top of the order revenue already booked and the same sales are counted twice, or order income and an unmatched bank deposit never reconcile; and Shopify Flow, free on every plan, can react to a payout event and notify you but has no action that decomposes a payout, matches it to a bank deposit, or writes a journal entry, so the one step that matters is the step it cannot take. Why it matters: a deposit booked as fresh income double counts revenue you already recorded, so your profit looks bigger than it is and you may overpay tax on money you never made; a payout forced to balance buries a refund or a fee in the wrong account so your margins lie to you; and a second gateway like PayPal or Shop Pay Installments deposits on its own schedule and nets its own fees, so the problem multiplies rather than adds. The big mistake is clicking Add on the Shopify deposit in the bank feed, the single most common ecommerce bookkeeping error, which records the deposit as a brand new income line and doubles your revenue while hiding the fees and refunds inside it. The usual workarounds break: a spreadsheet reconciliation turns a founder into a part-time bookkeeper and stops tying out the first time a payout spans a month boundary or a refund clears late; running more than one gateway means reconciling two or three streams of batched, netted deposits into one set of books; and the official connector books every deposit the same way, including the wrong ones. The AI playbook triggers when a payout settles or a deposit lands, decomposes it into gross sales, fees, refunds, chargebacks, adjustments, and reserve, matches every line back to the orders and refunds it came from, ties the net to the exact amount that hit the bank to the cent, categorizes sales, fees, refunds, and collected tax to the right accounts, splits each gateway on its own schedule and fees, holds any deposit that does not reconcile or is missing an order for review, and posts a clean matched entry while logging which orders rolled into it so the close is auditable and reversible. By Priya Singh, 2026-06-29.
- [How to bulk edit product prices on Shopify](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-bulk-edit-product-prices-on-shopify.html): Repricing a catalog in bulk is the quiet Shopify chore that scales with the size of your store, and the platform leaves the math entirely to a human. When a supplier cost rises, a tariff lands, or a margin slips, every affected price needs to move, and the native bulk editor only lets you type values: it has no formula, so you cannot say increase by ten percent, add a fixed amount, or round everything to end in .99 and have it compute each new price; it shows products a page at a time, commonly fifty, so a real catalog means batch after batch; and it does not expose variant prices in the same view as the parent, so a store with sizes or colors edits each variant on its own. Two partial fixes each solve only half: a CSV export lets you write a formula in a spreadsheet and import the result, but it risks overwriting descriptions, inventory, or other fields and makes the spreadsheet the source of truth for your storefront; and Shopify's percentage price adjustment lives under Markets and applies one percentage to an entire market's catalog rather than letting you selectively reprice your home catalog by vendor, collection, tag, or margin. Shopify Flow, free on every plan, can react when a product is updated, tag it, and notify you, but it has no action that sets a product or variant price, so it cannot raise prices by a percentage, apply a rounding rule, or reprice anything: it can tell you a cost changed, not act on it. Why it matters: pricing is the most financially direct field in the admin because it is the number people pay you, so a miscalculated percentage, a transposed digit that prices a forty dollar item at four, a missed variant, or a compare-at left in place so a raise reads as a fake discount all ship straight to every shopper, leaking margin or killing conversion until someone notices. The big mistake is treating it as data entry when it is selection and judgement: which products the change is really for, whether to compute from cost or current price, when compare-at should move or clear, and whether the rule would push an item below a margin floor or onto an absurd value. The usual workarounds break: the bulk editor cannot compute anything, so it is just faster hand-typing; the CSV is one bad cell away from overwriting live data; and a bulk price app applies a fixed rule you set in advance, including to the products the rule should not have touched. The AI playbook triggers on the reason (a cost change, a tariff or tax, a margin breach, or a planned reprice), selects the exact products and variants in scope by vendor, collection, tag, cost, or margin, computes a new price per item from a percentage, a fixed amount, or a target margin, applies your rounding and fixes compare-at so a raise does not read as a discount, holds anything below a margin floor or above a ceiling or on a strange value for review, writes the new price across every variant in one pass with no fifty-per-page batching, and logs the old price, the new price, and the rule so the change is auditable and reversible. By Priya Singh, 2026-06-28.
- [How to automatically add tracking numbers to Shopify orders](https://blog.dugong.live/how-to-automatically-add-tracking-numbers-to-shopify-orders.html): Entering tracking numbers is the quiet Shopify chore that scales linearly with how well you are selling, and the platform leaves it almost entirely to a human. Most physical orders do not fulfill themselves: for a self-shipped, supplier-shipped, or dropshipped order you open the order, hit mark as fulfilled, click into the tracking field, paste the number your supplier or warehouse emailed you, pick the carrier from a dropdown, save, and send the confirmation, one order at a time. Three concrete walls: auto-fulfillment only covers narrow cases (an entirely digital order, or items a connected fulfillment service or app controls and pushes its own tracking back for), so the everyday physical order defaults to manual; bulk fulfill and the CSV tracking import still leave the matching to you (bulk fulfill marks orders shipped but you attach each tracking number, and the CSV has to be assembled by hand with the right order numbers paired to the right tracking numbers and carriers, which is the exact job you were trying to avoid); and Shopify Flow, free on every plan, can react to an order, tag it, and notify you, but has no action that marks an order fulfilled with a specific tracking number and carrier read from a supplier email or feed, so the one step that clears the order is the step it cannot take, and an order assigned to a third-party fulfillment service location will not even show you the mark as fulfilled button (the service is meant to control the status, so when it is slow or silent you have to move items between locations to fulfill it yourself). Why it matters: the manual step is the most error-prone touch in the whole post-purchase flow, sitting right where the customer is paying closest attention, so a number pasted onto the wrong order, a dropped digit, a carrier dropdown left on the default, or a split